itioners and promoters of Daoism. Throughout are lively portrayals of encounters among the book's various characters-Chinese hermits and monks, Western seekers, and scholar-practitioners-as they interact with each other in obtuse, often humorous, and yet sometimes enlightening and transformative ways. Dream Trippers untangles the anxieties, confusions, and ambiguities that arise as Chinese and American practitioners balance cosmological attunement and radical spiritual individualism in their search for authenticity in a globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aGlobalizationxReligious aspectsxTaoism. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszChinazHua Mountain (Shaanxi Sheng) 0aSpiritualityxTaoism. 0aTaoismzUnited States. 0aTaoism. 0aTaoistszChina. 0aTaoistszUnited States. 4aChina. 4aDaoism. 4aNew Age. 4aauthenticity. 4aglobalization. 4amonasticism. 4aqigong. 4areligion. 4aspirituality. 4atourism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aSiegler, Elijah, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226484983423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226484983.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles